 POST: 🚀 Introducing OrbitDeck — A Full-Stack, Kubernetes-Native Deployment Platform!

Over the last few months, I’ve been quietly working on something that brings together my love for DevOps, backend engineering, and system design — and I’m thrilled to finally share it: OrbitDeck.

It’s not just a side project. It’s a full-blown modular PaaS that automates app deployment across Kubernetes clusters, with real-time updates, analytics, and task queues baked in. Imagine your own Heroku-style platform — only built from the ground up with modern infrastructure and a sleek React frontend.

📖 Want the full deep dive? I wrote a technical blog about the whole thing:


🔧 What’s under the hood?
🟣 A robust Go-based backend using Redis Pub/Sub, PostgreSQL, and Asynq task queues
🟣 Helm-powered deployment/uninstall workers running in isolated task queues
🟣 A Spring Boot microservice for real-time logging and analytics
🟣 A beautifully animated React.js frontend with dashboards, timelines, and live polling
🟣 Terraform-powered Azure AKS provisioning — secure, reproducible infra-as-code
🟣 Fully modular microservices — independently deployable and testable

From tracking deployment health and component usage to logging every event in Redis channels — the system is designed for deep observability and scalability. Infrastructure is code. And every action leaves a trace in the dashboard.

💡 This project pushed me on all fronts: distributed systems, infra-as-code, async workers, real-time UI, and scalable design — and I absolutely loved the grind.

